Here's a complete example wrapping a REST API as an MCP server with stdio transport.

## Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Fetch a resource by its unique identifier.")]
    public async Task<string> GetResource(
        [Description("The unique resource ID to look up")] string id,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching resource {Id}", id);
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/api/resources/{id}", cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Search resources by keyword query.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchResources(
        [Description("Search keyword")] string query,
        [Description("Max results to return (1-50)")] int limit = 10,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Searching for {Query}, limit {Limit}", query, limit);
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync(
            $"/api/resources?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(query)}&limit={limit}",
            cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool(Destructive = false, ReadOnly = true),
     Description("List all available resource categories.")]
    public async Task<string> ListCategories(
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync("/api/categories", cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

## Program.cs — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
    client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("Accept", "application/json");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|-------|-----------|---------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in the constructor (like `ApiTools` above) |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | DI services as method params alongside tool params |

**Key behavior:** The SDK automatically distinguishes tool parameters from injected services. Parameters like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, and `IProgress<T>` are **resolved from DI and never appear in the tool's JSON schema** exposed to the LLM. Only parameters with `[Description]` are visible to the LLM.

For the example above, `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` are injected via the constructor. The LLM only sees `id`, `query`, and `limit` as callable parameters.

### To scaffold this project from scratch:

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n MyApiServer
cd MyApiServer
dotnet build && dotnet run
```

This starts the server listening on stdin for JSON-RPC messages. Test it with [MCP Inspector](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/inspector) or configure it in your IDE's `mcp.json`.
